WEBVTT

00:01.538 --> 00:03.240
Hello family, Tyler here.

00:03.300 --> 00:13.695
I wanted to take a moment to invite you to Bridgetown's 8th Annual Holy Spirit Conference, January 23rd and 24th at Portland's, Colorado.

00:14.376 --> 00:18.622
The theme of this year's conference is going to be the healing after the healing.

00:19.143 --> 00:27.154
We'll be exploring how the miraculous work of the Holy Spirit is often just the first step to the deeper, slower soul level healing.

00:27.682 --> 00:36.015
Like the man-born blind in John 9, each part of us God heals only exposes a deeper part of us awaiting healing from the same God.

00:36.376 --> 00:39.701
And the deepest healing is often the slowest kind.

00:40.563 --> 00:48.556
We're so excited to be joined by contributors like Ruth Haley Barton, Kurt Thompson, Ken Shigamatsu, and Brooke Ligertwood.

00:49.017 --> 00:52.602
Tickets are available now at bridgetown.church.com.

00:52.843 --> 00:54.866
I hope you can join us.

01:06.914 --> 01:10.278
Mark chapter one, verses nine through 13.

01:13.562 --> 01:18.809
At that time, Jesus came from Nazareth in Galilee and was baptized by John in the Jordan.

01:19.830 --> 01:27.019
Just as Jesus was coming up out of the water, he saw heaven being torn open and the spirit descending on him like a dove.

01:27.880 --> 01:32.766
And a voice came from heaven, you are my son whom I love.

01:33.607 --> 01:35.890
With you, I am well pleased.

01:36.642 --> 01:43.229
at once the Spirit sent him out into the wilderness, and he was in the wilderness for 40 days, being tempted by Satan.

01:44.210 --> 01:45.151
This is the word of the Lord.

01:45.191 --> 01:46.993
Thanks be to God.

01:52.078 --> 02:03.890
A number of years ago, I was one among about a hundred in a cohort of Christian pastors doing quarterly retreats in this Midwestern monastery type setting.

02:04.162 --> 02:18.644
One such retreat was entirely themed around prayer, but the practice of prayer that we were prescribed was a type of prayer involving no words, just sitting in God's loving presence.

02:18.664 --> 02:28.960
And in my experience today, words were kind of like the key ingredient to prayer, like prayer without words, similar to ordering the fried chicken at a vegan restaurant.

02:29.561 --> 02:32.946
Sure, son, you've entirely lost the plot.

02:33.218 --> 02:48.082
I was committed to growing beyond my comfort zone and my current experience since I took the advice of the wise older woman who got all giddy talking about the joy of sitting in God's presence, doing nothing but receiving his love and silence.

02:48.962 --> 03:01.102
But then when I got back home to Brooklyn where I lived at the time and I sat out on the stoops of the apartment building that I called home just as the sun was dawning the following morning, I didn't feel all warm and fuzzy.

03:01.202 --> 03:05.910
I didn't have a heart-rending lightning bolt of divine revelation.

03:05.930 --> 03:08.434
I didn't really get it.

03:09.410 --> 03:11.373
I just felt restless and unproductive.

03:11.473 --> 03:13.776
I felt distracted and uncentered.

03:13.836 --> 03:20.505
I wondered in the back of my head how this could possibly be formative for me or pleasing to God.

03:21.046 --> 03:30.339
And mostly I just wondered if I was practicing the ancient way of Jesus or if I might just be beginning to completely lose it altogether.

03:31.680 --> 03:35.826
Tonight we're continuing a teaching series we began a week ago, a prayer shaped life.

03:35.906 --> 03:38.909
or we as a community are taking the long range view of prayer.

03:39.510 --> 03:48.400
Less, prayers immediate power in the world around me and more prayer slow formative power of the world within me.

03:48.821 --> 03:59.693
Now next month we're gonna get to the rhythm of prayer that orders and guides our days, but first in part one of the series, we're gonna talk about the way that prayer shapes us as apprentices of Jesus.

04:00.114 --> 04:04.018
How prayer is a means to be with Jesus, become like Jesus.

04:04.130 --> 04:05.431
and do what Jesus did.

04:05.872 --> 04:13.320
And up for tonight is prayer as being with Jesus through the practice of silent prayer.

04:14.001 --> 04:16.984
And that takes us back to Jesus' baptism.

04:17.525 --> 04:20.328
Look back down with me at your Bible's Mark chapter one.

04:20.368 --> 04:28.117
Just as Jesus was coming up out of the water, he saw heaven being torn open and the spirit descending on him like a dove.

04:28.597 --> 04:32.722
And a voice came from heaven, you are my son, whom I love.

04:33.218 --> 04:34.620
with you, I am well pleased.

04:35.642 --> 04:40.109
The whole of Jesus' life and ministry flows from this divinely given identity.

04:40.710 --> 04:50.867
Before his baptism, when the Father said, this is who you are, son, heir, beloved, wanted, welcomed, delighted him.

04:50.947 --> 04:59.762
Before all of that, Jesus lived for three decades without working a single miracle, calling a disciple, or uttering a word of teaching.

04:59.874 --> 05:06.422
After that divinely given identity, Jesus goes around distributing the same divine love everywhere he goes.

05:06.982 --> 05:11.468
The whole life and ministry of the incarnate God begins and ends with hearing the Father's voice.

05:12.028 --> 05:18.796
And the whole life of an apprentice to Jesus begins and ends with hearing the Father's voice.

05:19.457 --> 05:27.186
You are my daughter, my son, whom I love with you.

05:28.386 --> 05:29.707
I am well pleased.

05:31.349 --> 05:42.562
Three years after his baptism on the eve of his crucifixion, Jesus prays not only for the 12, but for all the generations of disciples who would come after them following him behind them.

05:42.602 --> 05:43.803
That's you and I tonight.

05:44.624 --> 05:52.112
And he prayed these words, then the world will know that you sent me and have loved them even as you have loved me.

05:52.172 --> 05:57.298
You, follower of Jesus, are clothed in the

05:57.506 --> 05:59.790
life and identity of Jesus.

06:00.731 --> 06:14.034
You are beloved, delighted, and heir to the riches of heaven itself, wanted, welcome, worthy, known, named, trusted,

06:14.178 --> 06:28.558
cherished, you are all of that graciously, a new identity that is given but never earned, irrevocably given and never returned, ungainable and therefore untakable, unlusable, unrejectable.

06:29.039 --> 06:35.688
That good, that real, that free, that permanent, that is where the life of a disciple begins and ends.

06:38.332 --> 06:42.418
All of which begs this obvious question.

06:44.130 --> 06:49.438
Why is this freely given beloved identity so slippery to hold on to?

06:51.461 --> 07:03.560
Why is it so easy to receive in a moment of comfort like this one so hard to hold on to tomorrow morning when I go to work or by midweek next week?

07:04.882 --> 07:09.970
Why is this freely given beloved identity so slippery to hold on to?

07:10.882 --> 07:14.907
Let me give you a sociological, a psychological, and a theological reason why.

07:14.947 --> 07:20.013
First, sociologically speaking, because you and I live in a noisy world.

07:21.055 --> 07:40.018
According to research from the University of Catalonia, in 2007, if you added up all the information taken in by a human being each day, think television, podcasts, books, notifications on your device, all of it, it would be the equivalent to reading 174, 85 page newspapers every day.

07:41.154 --> 07:47.370
We are fire-hosing our brains with content and information, far more information than anyone can actually process.

07:48.112 --> 07:55.090
We touch our phones on average 2617 times a day for an average of 3 hours and 15 minutes.

07:55.522 --> 07:57.845
We watch shows in the evenings, often over dinner.

07:58.246 --> 08:05.858
We listen to podcasts while we exercise and commute, or listen to music or audiobooks while we do the laundry or wash the dishes.

08:06.398 --> 08:14.010
You and I have developed a set of habits that makes quiet stillness and self-reflection so against our muscle memory it's next to impossible.

08:14.370 --> 08:17.475
We itch for distraction, for busyness, for productivity.

08:17.896 --> 08:22.162
So, of course, a man sitting on a Brooklyn stoop at dawn with

08:22.274 --> 08:30.804
Nothing to do, nothing to read, nothing to listen to, nothing to say, itches with the restlessness of an addict in need of a fix.

08:30.825 --> 08:33.828
We live in a noisy world with noisy minds.

08:34.589 --> 08:43.841
The psychologist and best-selling author Ethan Cross published a recent book titled Chatter, which is all about the cacophony of voices inside everyone's head.

08:44.581 --> 08:51.570
Negative rumination, that's the psychological term for the unfortunate fact that the unoccupied human mind

08:51.746 --> 08:53.789
always drifts toward fear.

08:54.811 --> 08:56.934
And you can save yourself reading his entire book.

08:56.954 --> 08:58.196
Here's the Cliffs Notes version.

08:58.256 --> 09:15.602
Negative rumination, that chatter in your unoccupied mind, it has the effect on you of either leading you to paralysis because you get stuck in a state of anger or frustration because you keep retelling yourself the same story about that person, that situation, or even about yourself.

09:16.258 --> 09:42.770
or transference, your anxiety about one thing comes out elsewhere, like frustration in a coworker being expressed as shortness toward your child or spouse or roommate back at home, or insecurity or self-loathing at very worst, you define yourself by that inner critic that rehearses the day's experiences, replying the moments you wish you had shown up to differently, or the moments you wish you had been received differently by those you showed up to.

09:43.266 --> 09:47.932
There's more noise in your head, in your inner world, even than in our outer world.

09:48.012 --> 09:53.819
And no matter what song you're listening to, the melody is fear, not love.

09:54.900 --> 09:59.065
We live in a noisy world with noisy minds and an ambitious culture.

09:59.626 --> 10:08.136
A 2024 study showed that Americans like more working hours exerting 42% more energy output than the European counterparts.

10:08.737 --> 10:09.938
And despite that,

10:10.274 --> 10:17.661
We were less efficient and productive than the vast majority of Western European nations, meaning you and I work ourselves to exhaustion.

10:17.721 --> 10:25.569
We are driven to succeed, and we do so even to the detriment of our own capacity, exceeding our limits, winning us diminishing returns.

10:25.990 --> 10:28.852
And that's just ambition when it gets channeled into work.

10:29.313 --> 10:38.642
Some more studies show that Americans lead the world in investment in cosmetic products, cosmetic procedures, dieting, and gym memberships.

10:38.754 --> 10:41.999
while also carrying some of the highest obesity rates in the world.

10:42.559 --> 10:46.826
We live in a culture that is ambitious for the most expiring parts of our lives.

10:47.266 --> 10:50.811
Our resumes, our waste sizes, and our physical appearances.

10:51.212 --> 10:57.481
But no one has ever said at a funeral, her abs were tight to the very end.

11:02.468 --> 11:06.514
We live in a noisy world with noisy minds.

11:10.754 --> 11:13.057
I'm going somewhere with all of this.

11:13.117 --> 11:21.567
Noisy worlds and noisy minds in an ambitious culture with distracted lives.

11:22.669 --> 11:33.362
Simply by living in Western culture, you and I are actively and intentionally being shaped to run from silence into the waiting and welcoming arms of distraction, entertainment and busyness.

11:33.410 --> 11:35.032
We live in an attention economy.

11:35.112 --> 11:38.557
Your imagination commodified by the little screen in your pocket.

11:38.897 --> 11:46.988
And we live in a social society, filling all of our quiet and alone moments with a barrage of noise through messages, notifications, and posts.

11:47.409 --> 11:55.159
Our minds are overworked, exhausted, and fragmented, the result of which is that we are reactionary and anxious at a psychologically alarming level.

11:55.860 --> 12:00.626
We live in a noisy world, a noisy mind, in an ambitious culture with distracted lives,

12:01.634 --> 12:03.557
and we have a quiet spirituality.

12:05.600 --> 12:11.148
Mark chapter six, then because so many people were coming and going, they did not even have a chance to eat.

12:11.248 --> 12:17.137
Jesus said to them, come with me by yourselves to a quiet place and get some rest.

12:18.399 --> 12:20.302
Jesus lived a quiet spirituality.

12:21.243 --> 12:24.949
He retreated often and invited his apprentices to do the same.

12:24.989 --> 12:27.092
And look, I don't want to overstate this.

12:27.833 --> 12:31.058
Jesus was active relational and interruptible.

12:31.842 --> 12:33.945
But you cannot miss the theme.

12:34.025 --> 12:42.695
If you give an honest reading of the gospels that Jesus prioritized, the slow, quiet way of being alone with the father who spoke over him first at his baptism.

12:43.556 --> 12:44.798
He retreated quietly.

12:44.818 --> 12:49.544
He left the crowds just as often as he sought them, and he taught us to do the same.

12:49.564 --> 12:55.070
A quiet inner life, it seems to me, is the canvas on which God paints his masterpieces.

12:56.672 --> 13:00.377
As a father of three young boys, I'm often called on to provide homework help.

13:00.537 --> 13:01.458
And while look,

13:01.666 --> 13:07.352
I will freely admit that I have googled many a math equation under the table while they weren't looking.

13:08.913 --> 13:11.136
I'm pretty good with grammar and logic.

13:11.696 --> 13:18.043
And one of the logic worksheets that I typically interact with involves the question, which one of these does not belong?

13:18.724 --> 13:23.769
Like one circle among a group of squares or one cat among a group of dogs, that kind of thing.

13:24.109 --> 13:28.754
So let's play a little game of which one of these does not belong.

13:28.962 --> 13:37.215
We live in a noisy culture with noisy minds in an ambitious world with distracted lives and a quiet spirituality.

13:38.156 --> 13:39.458
Do you see the issue here?

13:39.518 --> 13:42.743
One of these things is not like the others.

13:43.945 --> 13:48.131
Why is this freely given beloved identity so slippery to hold on to?

13:48.231 --> 13:50.074
Well, there you have a sociological reason.

13:51.076 --> 13:52.498
How about a psychological one?

13:53.442 --> 14:02.858
Psychologically speaking, attachment relationships between children and caregivers form our sense of self more than any other factor in human development.

14:02.878 --> 14:11.473
Attachment theory is among the world of psychology's most universally recognized and adopted ways of understanding the inner world of the individual.

14:12.054 --> 14:19.026
And attachment theory claims that the way that you show up relationally in the world as an adult is based mostly

14:19.138 --> 14:29.788
on the way that you experience security, insecurity, harm, neglect, abandonment, or trauma in your first relationship in this world with your caregiver.

14:30.889 --> 14:34.573
You see, the human brain is always developing shortcuts, and that's a really good thing.

14:34.673 --> 14:42.741
It's why you can drive a car and change lanes while having a conversation with someone in the passenger seat and needing a sandwich all at the same time.

14:43.381 --> 14:48.466
Without those sort of shortcuts in your brain, you would be concentrating hard on just

14:49.090 --> 14:55.119
clicking the turn signal and drifting into the left lane the way that you did at 15, the first time you ever drove on the highway.

14:55.961 --> 15:00.888
Your brain creates relational shortcuts too for your healing or for your harm.

15:00.948 --> 15:11.224
The experiences between child and guardian get chunked together into shortcuts the brain has made by piecing together patterns of felt experience.

15:11.244 --> 15:12.466
That's called attachment.

15:12.962 --> 15:21.641
The patterns we experience as children from our caregivers created shortcuts in our brains that inform how we experience all relationships today.

15:21.681 --> 15:27.794
Relationships with other people, the way that we view ourselves, even the way that we know and relate to God.

15:28.354 --> 15:38.466
We all have unique attachment patterns because we are all unique people with unique experiences, but over time in this field, four primary attachment styles have emerged.

15:38.847 --> 15:52.303
And without going into a full explanation of attachment theory, for our purposes this evening, I simply want to point out that psychologically speaking, healthy human attachment is called secure attachment.

15:53.185 --> 15:57.650
Dr. Todd Hall, who's both a clinical psychiatrist and a follower of Jesus' rights,

15:57.762 --> 16:01.987
To be securely attached means you are spoken for by your attachment figures.

16:02.448 --> 16:09.657
Secure attachment means someone in this world has signed up to look out for you, to always be for you.

16:11.119 --> 16:17.487
Amos, my three-year-old, is a pretty social kid, really friendly outgoing guy, very trusting.

16:18.488 --> 16:26.738
But if he bumps his head, not just anyone will do, he will run past all sorts of familiar faces.

16:26.850 --> 16:40.190
Friends he sees in this church community or often in my home, other family members, aunts, uncles, grandparents, he will run past everyone else looking for one of two faces, either me or Kirsten.

16:41.152 --> 16:41.893
Why is that?

16:43.315 --> 16:46.099
Well, I hope it's because he's growing securely attached.

16:47.060 --> 16:56.114
I hope it's because he feels spoken for by someone in this world, that there's someone that is always looking out for him, someone who is safe to run to when he's hurting.

16:57.090 --> 16:57.571
A.W.

16:57.631 --> 17:01.716
Tozer in the knowledge of the holy argues that we all know God in two different ways.

17:01.756 --> 17:04.179
We know God explicitly and implicitly.

17:04.880 --> 17:09.266
Your explicit knowledge of God is everything you cognitively believe about God.

17:09.426 --> 17:12.250
And it's the way that you would describe your faith.

17:12.370 --> 17:17.938
It's the scripture that you memorize, the doctrine that you recite, the lyrics to the songs that you sing.

17:17.978 --> 17:22.544
Implicit knowledge, on the other hand, is everything you relationally believe about God.

17:22.924 --> 17:27.090
And it is rooted primarily in your attachment style.

17:27.874 --> 17:36.046
Those with the mother or father wound like abandonment tend to have a hard time knowing God without fearing the same sort of abandonment from their heavenly father.

17:36.547 --> 17:45.801
Those with overbearing parents tend to relate to God like an overbearing parent, either tiptoeing around the rules or rebelling against whatever they perceive the rules to be.

17:45.841 --> 17:51.570
Those with performance-driven parents tend to relate to God like love as a reward for good performance.

17:52.098 --> 18:13.462
In the psychoanalyst, Anna Maria Rizzuto, argues from a robust amount of research on the psychology of prayer, the way you and I pray is actually less reflective of what we say we believe about God, and more reflective of the home that you grew up in, and the caregivers who shaped you first, and what made you feel safe or threatened in that environment.

18:14.383 --> 18:18.247
Consider your family of origin for a minute.

18:18.267 --> 18:20.530
I just try in your imagination to go back

18:21.442 --> 18:30.638
to the environment of your earliest years and the way that you related to the people who raised you.

18:32.261 --> 18:46.226
And with that home environment in mind, as honestly as you can, finish these two statements, the most important thing in life is, and I'm only safe when.

18:53.762 --> 19:06.161
Whatever your answers to those two questions are, there you have the great descriptors of the spiritual battle that you will fight longest and hardest to overcome, the lies the deceiver planted in you before you even had a chance to defend yourself.

19:07.222 --> 19:15.135
And a voice came from heaven saying, you are my son, whom I love, with you I am well pleased.

19:15.615 --> 19:20.082
Why is that freely given identity so slippery to actually hold on to?

19:20.738 --> 19:23.803
Well, there you have a sociological reason, a psychological reason.

19:23.843 --> 19:25.625
Now, how about a theological reason?

19:25.685 --> 19:33.617
Look back at your Bibles, and they want to pick up right after this moment where Jesus is spoken for by the Father as baptism, verse 12.

19:34.479 --> 19:41.169
At once, the Spirit sent him into the wilderness, and he was in the wilderness 40 days, being tempted by Satan.

19:41.830 --> 19:50.162
So as soon as the divine identity of love was given and received by Jesus, he suddenly poses a threat to the darkness of this world.

19:50.690 --> 19:59.806
and the serpent in the garden who stole that very identity from the first man and woman as soon as it is given to Jesus comes to try to take it from him too.

19:59.886 --> 20:07.559
You see, Mark chapter one is just a reenactment of Genesis chapters one, two, and three.

20:08.621 --> 20:16.434
Creation happened when a human being was spoken by God, spoken for by the God who is personified love.

20:16.546 --> 20:26.797
Deception happens when an enemy weaves a lie, a lie aimed at earning the love that I've already been freely given.

20:27.998 --> 20:30.141
You see, the forbidden fruit was never the point.

20:31.002 --> 20:34.205
The serpent never once asks Eve to eat the fruit.

20:34.706 --> 20:36.628
The focus of the temptation was never the fruit.

20:36.668 --> 20:39.931
You never hear the serpent saying anything like, look at that apple.

20:41.213 --> 20:42.574
Oh man, that looks good.

20:43.636 --> 20:45.938
I think it's a Fuji.

20:46.210 --> 20:47.613
Ooh, nope, it's a gala.

20:47.633 --> 20:48.214
You don't think.

20:48.775 --> 20:50.598
A cosmic crisp.

20:51.780 --> 20:53.944
You never hear anything like that.

20:54.746 --> 20:58.713
There's no direct temptation toward behavior or compromise in morality.

20:59.034 --> 21:07.910
Instead, the serpent just chips away at ease, trust, and God, until this moral action is the natural product of a relational deception.

21:08.651 --> 21:10.194
The lie is aimed at love.

21:10.786 --> 21:16.773
Where to find love, how to find love, who or what will love me, and even how I'm supposed to love another.

21:17.194 --> 21:28.307
This is why 2 Timothy 3 goes on to describe people corrupted by that ancient lie as lovers of themselves, lovers of money, and lovers of pleasure rather than lovers of God.

21:28.867 --> 21:34.314
Sin then is not the absence of love, but the search for love in a place I will never find it.

21:35.956 --> 21:38.098
Every human being is on a search for love.

21:38.722 --> 21:49.484
And sin is the attempt to acquire love by some means that is under my own control rather than receive it as the free gift of God who made me in his divine image.

21:50.587 --> 21:59.826
It is to try to drum up my own lovableness somehow, to try to become in my own eyes or in the eyes of everybody else what I already am in the eyes of God.

22:00.130 --> 22:12.830
to try to use my resume or my body or my accomplishments, my status, my calendar, my possessions, my social standing, my sense of security to become lovable to my preferred audience.

22:13.911 --> 22:19.220
The same serpent who lied to Eve lies to Jesus in three particular ways.

22:20.361 --> 22:28.434
Turn these stones into bread, jump off the temple and be rescued by angelic intervention and worship me and I'll give you your creation back.

22:29.090 --> 22:38.586
It is the same liar, weaving the same deception, aimed not at behavior but at love, chipping away at the identity of love that's just been spoken over Jesus as baptism.

22:39.748 --> 22:43.955
You are the one who can turn stones into bread, belovedness by provision.

22:45.157 --> 22:50.866
You are the one who can jump from the temple to spectacular rescue, belovedness by performance.

22:51.330 --> 23:06.624
You are the one who can rule the world, belovedness by power, each temptation, some version of, earn what God just gave you, drum up your own lovableness, but come in your eyes or in everybody else's eyes what you already are in the eyes of the Father.

23:06.945 --> 23:09.367
And again and again and again, what does Jesus say?

23:09.387 --> 23:13.451
No, no, no, I am the beloved of God.

23:15.793 --> 23:19.156
That is who I've already been named and I will not let you redefine me.

23:20.457 --> 23:21.298
Prayer then.

23:21.634 --> 23:34.274
is first listening to that voice, to the Father's voice, the one who spoke me first and who speaks for me, each and every time I stop and slow myself to listen.

23:34.334 --> 23:44.210
And hearing that voice, the one who speaks love over me and a whisper, that requires intention and practice for people like us.

23:45.378 --> 23:52.869
people who live in a noisy world with noisy minds and an ambitious culture with distracted lives and a quiet spirituality.

23:54.090 --> 24:00.539
People whose image of God is as distorted as the warped version of love that was offered us in the homes we grew up in.

24:01.761 --> 24:07.850
Richard Foster writes, in contemporary society our adversary, that's a biblical title for Satan.

24:08.651 --> 24:13.618
In contemporary society our adversary majors in three things, noise, hurry, and crowds,

24:14.178 --> 24:19.084
If he can keep us engaged in muchness and manyness, he will rest satisfied.

24:20.446 --> 24:24.150
Why is this freely given beloved identity so slippery to hold on to?

24:24.611 --> 24:27.515
Because we think muchness and manyness is where love is found.

24:28.856 --> 24:37.227
We are searching for love, scrambling for love, but Jesus returned to that love alone and in the quiet.

24:38.048 --> 24:39.890
And that's where you and I will find it too.

24:41.698 --> 24:50.129
Octavia Bright wrote this beautiful memoir documenting her first five years of sobriety and her journey out of alcoholism.

24:50.149 --> 24:57.579
A sobriety journeyed it for her coincided with the loss of her father in the subsequent grieving process.

24:58.641 --> 25:06.992
And in one scene in her story, she's sitting beside the bed of her dying father under these bright hospital lights considering her own journey toward wholeness.

25:07.693 --> 25:08.594
And she writes,

25:09.410 --> 25:19.704
There I could see the flaw in my desire for a sense of continuous progress, which can't help but suggest a perpetual movement towards something better or a destination at which you can arrive.

25:20.285 --> 25:26.854
Sometimes, recovery is not about moving forward, but about being able to stay still.

25:28.336 --> 25:28.937
And that's it.

25:30.399 --> 25:38.130
In this jungle of muchness and manyness lies, we do not find our way out by movement and active steps of progress, we learn to be still.

25:38.946 --> 25:49.397
to wait, to grow quiet, still patient and quiet enough to stop searching for love, but to let love find me.

25:51.058 --> 26:01.569
To let love find me again today so that when I do move, it is from the spoken for identity that threatens every square inch of darkness in this world around me.

26:02.630 --> 26:06.194
And that is how being with Jesus

26:06.306 --> 26:15.397
receiving the very love he received that is mine in Christ and living from that foundation he returned to again and again and again.

26:15.417 --> 26:20.903
That is how being with Jesus is practiced through silent prayer.

26:21.964 --> 26:27.251
Silent prayer is the active practice of remaining in the love of God.

26:28.412 --> 26:30.194
It is the active choice

26:30.274 --> 26:41.689
to retreat from the muchness and manyness into the quiet where I hear again today the love that spoke me into being at first and speaks over me afresh each day.

26:43.451 --> 26:55.807
So there I was, pastor of a community of Jesus' apprentices, trying my best to live a quiet spirituality and keep up in a muchness and manyness culture both at the same time.

26:56.988 --> 26:58.290
Feeling foolish,

26:58.658 --> 27:12.463
on a Brooklyn stoop at dawn with nothing to do but wait, wondering why nothing was happening and how long I'm supposed to wait on something to happen, itching for some kind of noise to sate my restless attention.

27:13.866 --> 27:19.536
There I was years ago and there I hope you will have been by this time tomorrow.

27:20.478 --> 27:22.802
So we better get practical about all of this.

27:23.650 --> 27:29.758
in the world of recovery in which Octavia found the strength to stay still and surrender.

27:30.099 --> 27:33.303
They've got this mantra and it goes something like this.

27:33.524 --> 27:34.966
It works if you work it.

27:36.047 --> 27:41.775
So that'll do for us for a little turn from theory and then to practice.

27:41.795 --> 27:43.117
Okay, silent prayer.

27:43.557 --> 27:46.461
How does it work and how do I work it?

27:47.763 --> 27:48.744
First, how does it work?

27:48.805 --> 27:49.906
Silent prayer

27:49.986 --> 27:59.041
is the, sorry, silent prayer in the presence of God is the practice of receiving the love of the Father and then sharing that same divine love with others.

28:00.042 --> 28:02.326
So first, let's talk about receiving the love of the Father.

28:03.147 --> 28:17.010
Tanya Lourman, whose anthropological research I referenced a week ago, wrote this fascinating book on the psychology of all spiritual practices from different spiritualities and religions titled, How God Becomes Real.

28:17.442 --> 28:29.682
And in her finding, she discovered that across the board in modern religious communities and among different spiritual practitioners, quote, it is more difficult to sustain belief in a loving God than a demonic spirit.

28:30.323 --> 28:32.707
Across these faiths runs a common thread.

28:32.747 --> 28:38.136
That which we fear is more believable than that for which we yearn.

28:39.278 --> 28:43.986
You see, we live in a culture where fear is the air that we breathe that requires no intention.

28:44.258 --> 28:49.083
We live in a culture where silence is endangered at best and outright extinct more likely.

28:49.523 --> 28:52.427
And so it requires priority and practice.

28:52.447 --> 28:56.691
Silent prayer is the intentional practice of belief in a loving God.

28:57.131 --> 29:01.676
Muchness and manyness is the passive practice of belief in a cunning deceiver.

29:03.258 --> 29:06.841
Personally, I come from a long family line of doers.

29:06.922 --> 29:11.186
We are active and reliable at our very best and hurried busy bodies at our worst.

29:11.746 --> 29:17.636
Also, I have a personality structure that happens to be bent in the direction of activity, productivity, and achievement.

29:18.417 --> 29:28.795
And I've chosen a vocation that is made up heavily of preaching and writing, where I'm identified by, where what most people want from me to state it most crassly, is what I do.

29:28.895 --> 29:31.419
It is the words that I produce.

29:31.880 --> 29:33.042
So there you have.

29:33.826 --> 29:49.547
the personality through which I process and participate in our noisy world, the psychology of my family history, my attachment patterns in a nutshell, and the vocation that can so effortlessly for me just be an outlet to more muchness and meaningness.

29:49.847 --> 29:59.941
So the overlap of that Venn diagram for me personally is a spirituality that is highly susceptible of being bent in the direction of overdoing it.

30:00.321 --> 30:00.862
That's me.

30:00.882 --> 30:03.826
It might not necessarily be you.

30:04.834 --> 30:09.300
In silent prayer, then, I am still quiet and alone.

30:11.022 --> 30:11.843
There's no doing.

30:12.103 --> 30:13.104
There's no activity.

30:13.124 --> 30:14.346
There's nothing to achieve.

30:15.688 --> 30:17.189
I'm bringing nothing to God.

30:17.270 --> 30:22.056
Save a set of open hands and an attempt at an attentive imagination.

30:22.756 --> 30:30.386
I've come with no words that commodity that I trade in vocationally.

30:31.362 --> 30:45.235
that thing that I'm so used to, everyone else wanting from me, some string of words that might inspire or instruct or comfort, I'm coming to God with nothing that makes me feel useful in this world.

30:46.857 --> 30:53.824
Silent prayer is the place where I come to God naked and unashamed of everything that makes me feel useful.

30:54.424 --> 31:00.530
And it is where I discover Him there seeing me, knowing me, loving me,

31:01.058 --> 31:07.484
choosing me entirely apart from all of my usefulness.

31:08.725 --> 31:31.026
And that is how for me being still and quiet in the presence of God is the furnace that burns away the false places that I go looking for love and refines the only love that I possess that is real enough to keep the perfect kind of love that casts all the fear out of my life spoken over me afresh today.

31:31.938 --> 31:34.201
That's how silent prayer works within me.

31:35.343 --> 31:37.046
There's even more to it than that, though.

31:38.308 --> 31:42.173
You know, every Sunday, I have the great privilege of getting to pray and preach in pastor.

31:42.233 --> 31:47.441
But do you know what the most spiritually formative moment of my Sunday is every week?

31:48.783 --> 31:50.686
It's not the ministering or the teaching.

31:50.726 --> 31:53.851
It is not the listening or the pastoring.

31:53.891 --> 31:54.913
It's none of the doing.

31:56.074 --> 31:58.578
It's the moment that I get home from all of that.

31:59.682 --> 32:03.346
And I walk into the door and I'm welcomed by Kirsten Hanks.

32:03.366 --> 32:13.736
I'm in a little Amos by my family because they are so glad to see me, but they don't want from me what everyone else has been wanting from me all day long.

32:14.256 --> 32:22.985
Words, my version of doing and producing and achieving, now they could care less about any of my usefulness.

32:24.226 --> 32:27.890
They just want me to be with me.

32:28.994 --> 32:34.983
to welcome me, to accept me, to see me, to love me, and to be loved by me.

32:36.085 --> 32:40.932
And the neighbors, friends, and coworkers that I've grown closest to over the years, it's the same with all of them.

32:41.973 --> 32:58.418
The very same love that I quietly and intentionally practice receiving from God in silent prayer, I go on unintentionally receiving in all the relational spaces of my active life when I get up from that moment of silent prayer.

32:58.978 --> 33:27.698
And as I experience the naked and unashamed love of God in silent prayer, and that same love of God coming to me through others, something like scales are slowly but surely beginning to fall from my eyes, and I'm beginning to see others the same way, to draw little by little more capable of welcoming others into my loving presence in the very way that I'm welcomed into the loving presence of God, to see

33:27.874 --> 33:32.320
and accept others for their being and not their usefulness.

33:33.321 --> 33:37.547
To welcome them in the very welcome of the God who knows them best and loves them most.

33:37.567 --> 33:52.466
You see, what I'm trying to show you very personally is that when you show up to silent prayer, you might at first discover that it charades as a private practice, but the truth is that it is profoundly communal.

33:52.930 --> 33:57.156
It is prayer that begins privately, but then pours out of us compassionately.

33:57.497 --> 34:05.549
It is the practice of being alone with God for a moment so that I can be truly, richly and deeply with others for a lifetime.

34:05.969 --> 34:11.858
That's how silent prayer works through me, sharing the same divine love with others.

34:12.610 --> 34:34.320
One of the enemy's most subtle but debilitating blows to our generation is to take this very good, growing re-engagement with ancient, forgotten spiritual practices and then warp them into self-serving lifestyle hacks that we engage to feel better or achieve balance like it's the spiritual version of drinking powdered greens and sitting in red light therapy solanas.

34:35.081 --> 34:41.490
When the truth is that every spiritual practice, including silent prayer, is a means to an end.

34:41.954 --> 34:50.025
That end is being poured out like a drink offering in the language of the Apostle Paul, an offering of sacrificial love for the sake of the world.

34:50.866 --> 34:56.233
Thomas Merton says, we do not go into the desert to escape people but to learn how to find them.

34:56.693 --> 35:03.903
We do not leave them in order to have nothing more to do with them but to find out the way to do them the most good.

35:05.124 --> 35:09.490
Silent prayer is a way of being crucified with Christ for the sake of the world.

35:10.178 --> 35:17.478
Henry Nowhan defines this quietest way of prayer as listening to God and listening to the pains of the world simultaneously.

35:18.180 --> 35:26.002
To return to his definition of prayer from a week ago, prayer always leads us to the heart of God and the heart of the human struggle at the same time.

35:26.690 --> 35:46.642
You see, when our lives are cluttered with so much coming and going, so much talking and doing, so much task management and achievement and getting from here to there and so little quiet in the presence of God, we are slowly but surely bent in the direction of using people rather than seeing, knowing, welcoming and loving them.

35:47.458 --> 35:57.327
We want to fix someone to get from someone to check another item off our list to commodify someone, but we cannot love that someone because we are out of step with the one who is love.

35:58.308 --> 36:10.140
If we do not learn to retreat from the crowd to listen to the Father like Jesus, then neither can we learn to see, welcome, and companion those within the crowd like Jesus.

36:11.241 --> 36:16.626
Dr. Jerry Sitzer says, Silent Prayer then is both a means and an end.

36:17.122 --> 36:18.824
It is a discipline we practice.

36:18.924 --> 36:20.286
It is a gift we receive.

36:21.147 --> 36:33.083
Such prayer, wordless, silent, patient, confident, secure will empty us and fill us, will break us and restore us, will plunge us into the darkness and draw us into the light.

36:33.583 --> 36:39.191
Separate us from God as we know Him through creation so that we can be united with God as we know Him in Christ.

36:39.531 --> 36:44.818
And thus we experience the union with Him for which our souls truly long.

36:46.146 --> 36:53.879
This definition, it upends the most common misconception about silent prayer carried by sincere apprentices of Jesus.

36:54.320 --> 36:59.488
And that is we get quiet so we can hear God speak.

37:01.812 --> 37:04.477
And sometimes God does speak.

37:04.497 --> 37:12.530
But the practice of silent prayer is a whole lot more about identity than it is about instruction.

37:13.666 --> 37:21.253
Listening prayer, tuning my ear to God, that's for the sake of new revelation, often on behalf of someone else.

37:21.273 --> 37:26.879
Silent prayer, though, is the practice of being in God's presence naked and unashamed.

37:27.840 --> 37:33.145
That I might be found by the love that I am ever tempted to go searching somewhere else for.

37:34.206 --> 37:36.688
Silent prayer explained as simply as possible.

37:37.329 --> 37:42.514
It's just the spiritual practice of being still and quiet in the presence of God.

37:43.266 --> 37:44.588
the God who is love.

37:45.550 --> 37:46.411
That's how it works.

37:47.653 --> 37:48.956
All right, so how do I work it?

37:49.557 --> 37:53.123
Well, here's the practice of silent prayer in four essential steps.

37:53.724 --> 38:00.836
First, you're going to need to choose a time and a place because any new habit requires you to cultivate a set time and place.

38:01.096 --> 38:04.041
Every new ritual is absolutely doomed without both of those.

38:04.642 --> 38:09.330
So when are you going to get quiet and still in the presence of God each day?

38:09.986 --> 38:13.250
Is it gonna be first thing in the morning or maybe the last thing before you go to bed?

38:13.310 --> 38:19.196
Is it gonna be during your daughter's nap time or in that 15 minute window you have between classes mid-morning?

38:19.937 --> 38:28.266
There's no magic hour, just choose a time when you tend to be alert rather than tired and a time that you can keep consistently when you won't be interrupted.

38:28.527 --> 38:32.731
And then where are you gonna get quiet and still in the presence of God?

38:33.693 --> 38:38.578
I guess there's a sacred chair in your living room that you love to sit in or a quiet bench

38:38.850 --> 38:43.254
outside of your office that you can stop by before you commute home in the evenings.

38:43.955 --> 38:58.009
There's no location, there's more wholly than any other in God's creation, so just choose somewhere that you can consistently hide away where you can be uninterrupted by distraction and uncluttered by anything else mentally.

38:58.910 --> 39:04.095
And then create a ritual of transition that will guide you from noise to quiet.

39:05.016 --> 39:06.738
Now as strange as this sounds,

39:07.042 --> 39:09.866
Quiet and still actually takes a lot of practice.

39:10.627 --> 39:18.898
So you're going to need to create some kind of ritual to transition from the external and internal noise that you're very used to into quiet.

39:20.080 --> 39:27.990
And that can be as simple as just lighting a candle or playing a sacred chime or sound or a short chorus of a song.

39:28.030 --> 39:33.097
It can be just taking three deep breaths to slow and study yourself.

39:33.157 --> 39:36.722
Whatever works, just pick a ritual and then use it every time.

39:37.058 --> 39:45.726
And if you're just starting out in this, I would highly recommend the Thomas Keating's app Centering Prayer, which is absolutely free.

39:45.766 --> 39:51.912
You can download it from the app store and it allows you to choose a sound and a timer that will begin and end your silence.

39:52.333 --> 39:59.239
So you can choose a chime that's unique, like not the same sound for the notifications for everything else on your phone.

39:59.920 --> 40:02.142
And you can choose a time frame that's manageable.

40:02.202 --> 40:06.546
You can set a clock for one minute or two minutes or 10 minutes.

40:06.626 --> 40:09.290
Don't be aspirational about your silence.

40:09.350 --> 40:10.211
Be consistent.

40:11.133 --> 40:20.026
Give God just a little bit of time to work with and show up day after day after day and see what He can do with that.

40:21.008 --> 40:24.513
And then finally, or thirdly, use breath prayer as an anchor.

40:25.234 --> 40:26.596
Look, you're going to get distracted.

40:27.578 --> 40:28.319
You just will.

40:29.080 --> 40:35.570
Saints don't have history of God distracted, and they were indoctrinated to a whole lot less noise than you and I are.

40:36.290 --> 40:40.657
Thankfully though, we have the time tested sacred practice of a breath prayer to anchor us.

40:41.278 --> 40:43.562
And a breath prayer is exactly what it sounds like.

40:43.642 --> 40:45.945
It is a prayer that you can pray in a single breath.

40:46.687 --> 40:58.826
So just pick a breath prayer and then pray that aloud every time you notice that your mind has wandered, just as a way of pulling you back to the attentiveness to the presence of God or you intended to stay.

40:59.447 --> 41:00.188
Here's how it works.

41:00.228 --> 41:03.794
Let's say that you just simply picked the name of Jesus and it would go like this.

41:05.506 --> 41:06.067
Jesus.

41:09.271 --> 41:11.514
Now I'm thinking about that text that I forgot to send.

41:11.554 --> 41:13.656
Jesus.

41:16.320 --> 41:20.706
Now I'm wondering if the chicken from four nights ago is still safe to eat for lunch today.

41:23.609 --> 41:24.170
Jesus.

41:26.433 --> 41:31.099
Now I'm ruminating on that unresolved argument that I'm having with my sister in Minnesota.

41:31.139 --> 41:33.522
Jesus.

41:35.074 --> 41:39.140
Now I'm thinking about how awful it would be to live in Minnesota where it's so cold.

41:40.182 --> 41:43.107
You know, Jesus, you get it, okay?

41:44.649 --> 41:54.485
Other really common breath prayers, sometimes involve something you can pray in an inhale and an exhale, something like, you are my beloved in whom I delight.

41:56.207 --> 42:02.898
Or in you, I live in you, I rest.

42:03.970 --> 42:07.254
For me, I just pray holy spirits.

42:08.715 --> 42:10.257
Just don't overthink it.

42:10.978 --> 42:14.021
Pick what works for you and use it as an anchor.

42:14.782 --> 42:17.365
And then fourth and finally, persevere.

42:18.026 --> 42:22.651
Because this quiet and alone way of being with God, it requires perseverance.

42:23.371 --> 42:32.882
The very person who knows they need solitude, stillness, and silent prayer the most is also the person who's going to have the hardest time observing it.

42:33.954 --> 42:48.289
You will quiet down for a few minutes or you will book that retreat at the monastery and you will tell everyone that you're going to retreat and slow down and cultivate this new way of being and then like me on that Brooklyn stoop, you will itch for activity and distraction.

42:48.369 --> 42:53.855
You will want entertainment, task and some measurable verifiable sense of progress.

42:54.176 --> 42:58.140
Your fragmented mind will hate the feeling of collecting itself.

42:58.560 --> 43:00.082
It will itch for noise.

43:00.930 --> 43:14.529
One ancient Christian writer describes the first stages and silent prayers, the experience of someone who has lived forever with an open door policy for their neighbors, and then all of a sudden one day without any explanation, they just shut and bolt the door.

43:16.071 --> 43:16.992
And then what happens?

43:17.032 --> 43:21.458
All the neighbors, the visitors who are used to coming and going as they please begin to

43:22.210 --> 43:36.916
knock and bang at the door, wondering why they're not allowed to enter, and it is only after a long, annoying wait inside the locked house that those visitors finally realize that they are not welcome and stop coming.

43:37.297 --> 43:39.060
Who are the visitors who are banging?

43:39.100 --> 43:42.706
They're the noisy voices of your ego.

43:43.490 --> 43:48.276
The false self that is too childish to go neglected for even a minute or two.

43:48.336 --> 44:07.177
The task of silent prayer then begins with just staying in my cell, just outlasting my visitors, waiting until they get exhausted from all their pounding and finally leaving me alone, because those who give in to distraction can be sure that it's just going to come for them quicker the next time.

44:08.259 --> 44:11.282
To put it bluntly, if you want to know the fruit of silent prayer,

44:11.682 --> 44:19.474
Be prepared to persevere through the awkward itchy restlessness that will surely haunt your early days in the practice of silent prayer.

44:19.906 --> 44:21.628
Persevere in your solitude.

44:22.108 --> 44:27.514
That is the way to the love that spoke you first and the love that speaks over you anew each day.

44:27.975 --> 44:44.432
It's the secure attachment of being spoken for by God himself and a deceived world full of lies and noise and the reward for those who persevere is that these visitors they bang less and less frequently until one day they retreat altogether.

44:45.714 --> 44:49.618
And silent prayer isn't only something that you practice from time

44:49.698 --> 45:03.590
to time your inner life has become quiet, so that you are able to go about the noise and hurry and frenzy of the crowds only doing what you see the Father doing in the words of Jesus.

45:04.772 --> 45:07.218
And as I look across biblical and church history,

45:08.706 --> 45:20.102
as I look at the lives of all the saints, meaning those who have cultivated such a depth with God that their life echoes far beyond their days, calling to the depths within you and me even tonight.

45:20.182 --> 45:33.801
As I look and search for what do all of these saints, so shaped by Jesus, have in common, I just see this one thing, that each and every one of them possess a quiet inner life in a very noisy and contested world.

45:35.023 --> 45:37.106
A quiet inner life, it seems to me,

45:38.050 --> 45:41.014
is the canvas on which God paints His masterpieces.

45:42.355 --> 45:48.403
So choose a time and place, create a ritual of transition, use a breath, prayers, an anchor, and persevere.

45:48.904 --> 45:50.065
That is how you work it.

45:50.906 --> 46:00.018
So the practice for this entire teaching series is prayer, and the exercise that we're going to engage as we gather in our Bridgestone communities this week around the table is prophetic prayer.

46:00.354 --> 46:05.701
as we listen and pray for one another based on the prayer training that we held in this room this past Tuesday evening.

46:06.062 --> 46:21.884
But because prophetic prayer is a communal exercise of quietly listening to God, we also want to equip everyone in our Georgetown communities with silent prayer as an individual exercise to carry into the week ahead for being with Jesus in the love of the Father.

46:23.326 --> 46:24.548
But for tonight we'll land here.

46:26.230 --> 46:29.234
I kept on showing up restlessly to that Brooklyn stoop.

46:30.082 --> 46:31.424
morning by morning.

46:32.925 --> 46:37.191
And as I did very, very slowly and subtly, the strangest thing happened to me.

46:38.753 --> 46:40.194
My noisy mind quieted.

46:40.234 --> 46:41.816
All those questions stilled.

46:41.856 --> 46:43.919
My restlessness finally came to rest.

46:44.740 --> 46:48.104
And when I was quiet, love found me there.

46:49.806 --> 46:59.698
And today, at this point in my apprenticeship to Jesus, there is no more essential practice for me than the practice of silent prayer.

47:00.834 --> 47:12.209
because I have discovered that this side of persevering through all my banging visitors silent prayer is that sacred place where I let my masks fall in the language of the ancient Christian Catechism.

47:13.310 --> 47:22.642
It is where I received the divine love that Jesus prayed would be mine, the only foundation I've found through which I can live in concert with that love and the noise of my days.

47:23.682 --> 47:34.057
And that practice of quiet stillness, it is increasingly forming me into the sort of person who is more attuned to that very same divine love coming to me in the course of all of my ordinary days.

47:35.239 --> 47:52.024
In the crisp fall air that I feel on my commute into work, and in the laughter that I hear in my children, the love of the father that I see in the knowing gaze of my wife, and the taste of the bread that I break with my community.

47:52.685 --> 47:53.426
God,

47:53.538 --> 47:54.679
loves you, friends.

47:56.802 --> 47:57.683
God loves you.

47:59.325 --> 48:04.051
He loves you too much to wait on you to come and find him.

48:05.593 --> 48:19.751
He loves you so much that he will come and find you if only you will stay still long enough quietly enough to be found.

48:21.193 --> 48:22.034
Why don't we stand?

48:22.818 --> 48:30.666
and we'll give him our quiet attention even now.

48:30.686 --> 48:34.510
Thanks for joining the Bridgestown family as we engage in this teaching series.

48:35.231 --> 48:41.177
To learn more about the life of our church and how you can get involved, visit bridgestown.church.com.

48:41.938 --> 48:50.226
If you're interested in contributing financially to Bridgestown Church and to our ministry, you can do that at bridgestown.church.gov.

48:50.754 --> 49:00.146
Wherever you're joining us from, we hope this resource blesses you and encourages you to be with Jesus, become like Jesus, and do what Jesus did.

